<subSubSection id="C357655BFFEA1738FF178940FACB5A31" box="[201,1332,1127,1151]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BF236D0FFEA1738FF178940FACB5A31" blockId="7.[151,1436,151,1223]" box="[201,1332,1127,1151]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis id="B939EAC2FFEA1738FF178940FEB75A31" bold="true" box="[201,328,1127,1151]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Etymology</emphasis>
. The species name refers to the triangular (
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D53FFEA1738FCF28940FC995A31" box="[812,870,1127,1151]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Igerna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="delta">delta</taxonomicName>
) subapical process on the aedeagal shaft.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C357655BFFEA1738FF1789ACFBCB5A89" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BF236D0FFEA1738FF1789ACFBCB5A89" blockId="7.[151,1436,151,1223]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis id="B939EAC2FFEA1738FF1789ACFEC95AED" bold="true" box="[201,310,1163,1187]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D53FFEA1738FE9A89ABFE325AED" box="[324,461,1163,1187]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Igerna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="delta">
<emphasis id="B939EAC2FFEA1738FE9A89ABFE325AED" box="[324,461,1163,1187]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Igerna delta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from other species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D53FFEA1738FC6D89ABFC015AED" box="[947,1022,1164,1187]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Igerna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B939EAC2FFEA1738FC6D89ABFC015AED" box="[947,1022,1164,1187]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Igerna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the subapical triangular lamellate expansion on the aedeagal shaft and apical pair of acute processes twisted ventrad.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
